{
  "response_text": "The cumulative number of prey deaths begins at zero and shows a strong upward trend for the initial 1,159 time steps. This initial surge corresponds to the period of highest predation pressure, where 20 foragers efficiently deplete the accessible portion of the 250 initial animals. The average mortality count reaches a peak of approximately 240 deaths around step 1,876. Towards the end of the simulation at step 2,311, the mean value is recorded at 235, indicating that the rate of death accumulation slows and stabilizes after the initial phase.\n\nTrend analysis using rolling windows confirms a significant positive direction for the first 928 steps, reflecting the active phase of the extinction pressure. Between steps 1,160 and 1,391, the trend becomes statistically insignificant, marking a transition where the marginal death rate drops. A subsequent decreasing trend is observed between steps 1,856 and 2,087 in the aggregate mean, aligning with the peak and tail-off of the mortality curve. The standard deviation of 65 across the 40 simulation runs indicates moderate stochasticity in individual outcomes, yet the central tendency remains robust under the set parameters of movement costs and forager density."
}

